{"title_page": "Divya Bharti", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian actress}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=August 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Divya Bharti\n| image              = Divya Bharti.jpg\n| image_size         = \n| caption            = Bharti in 1993\n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|df=yes|1974|02|25}}\n| birth_place        = [[Mumbai]]\n| death_date         = {{Death date |df=yes|1993|04|05|1974|2|25}} (age 19)\n| death_place        = [[Versova, Mumbai]]\n| death_cause        = Accidental fall\n| nationality        = Indian\n| occupation         = Actress\n| image_caption      = Divya Bharti in 1992\n| height             = 5 feet 6 inches (168 cm)\n| yearsactive        = 1990\u20131993\n| spouse             = [[Sajid Nadiadwala]]<br><small>(1992 \u20131993; her death)</small>\n}}\n\n'''Divya Bharti''' (25 February 1974 \u2013 5 April 1993) was an Indian film actress, who starred in a number of commercially successful [[Hindi cinema|Hindi]] and [[Telugu cinema|Telugu]] motion pictures in the early 1990s.Known for her acting versatility, vivacity and beauty, she is regarded as one of the most popular & highest paid actresses of her time.|[{Hindustan Times}]dated 05/04/20|\n\nBharti aspired to a career in films at a young age and started to get offers at age 14, while she was doing some modeling assignments. After several unsuccessful attempts, she made her debut with a lead role in the successful [[Cinema of Andhra Pradesh|Telugu]] drama ''[[Bobbili Raja]]'' (1990) at age 16. After featuring in a number of high-grossing Telugu films, she progressed to [[Bollywood|Hindi cinema]] in 1992 with the action thriller ''[[Vishwatma]]''. Bharti went on to have commercial success, appearing in films such as ''[[Shola Aur Shabnam (1992 film)|Shola Aur Shabnam]]'' and ''[[Deewana (1992 film)|Deewana]]'', the latter of which led to her winning the [[Filmfare Award for Best Female Debut]].<ref name=\"actress\">{{cite news|title=Shah Rukh Khan's autobiography Twenty Years In A Decade to release soon|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report_shah-rukh-khan-s-autobiography-twenty-years-in-a-decade-to-release-soon_1552261|accessdate=28 July 2012|newspaper=[[Daily News and Analysis]]|date=7 June 2011}}</ref> She acted in over a dozen consistently-successful Hindi films over a year span, which is to date an unbroken record in [[Hindi cinema]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://daily.bhaskar.com/article/divya-bharti-created-world-record-1541276.html|title=Divya Bharti created world record|work=daily.bhaskar.com|accessdate=27 September 2015|date=12 November 2010}}</ref> \n\nBharti died on 5 April 1993, aged 19,<ref name=Rediff>{{cite web|title=Looking at stars who died young|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-death-anniversary-of-divya-bharti-and-kurt-cobain/20110405.htm|publisher=[[Rediff.com]]|accessdate=27 December 2011|date=26 December 2011}}</ref> from head injuries sustained after falling off the balcony of her fifth-floor apartment at [[Versova, Mumbai]]. She was at a high-time in her career at the time of her death, and due to this had received significant speculation from the Indian film industry and audiences.<ref name=\"life on screen\">{{cite news|author=Chopra, Sonia|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-04-07/news-interviews/31300649_1_biopic-bollywood-debut-mystery|newspaper=[[The Times of India]]|title=Divya's journey: The 'ageless' diva over the years|date=7 April 2008|accessdate=19 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The sad truth: Celebs who committed suicide|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/gallery/actresses-who-committed-suicide-jiah-khan-kuldeep-randhawa-divya-bharti-in-their-prime/10/11881.html|website=[[India Today]]|accessdate=19 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and family==\nDivya Bharti was born in [[Bombay]] (present-day [[Mumbai]]) to Om Prakash Bharti, an insurance officer, and his wife, Meeta Bharti.<ref name=\"SaariCa\u1e6d\u1e6dop\u0101dhy\u0101\u1e8fa2009\">{{cite book|author1=Anil Saari|author2=P\u0101rtha Ca\u1e6d\u1e6dop\u0101dhy\u0101\u1e8fa|title=Hindi Cinema: An Insider's View|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dqzQOgAACAAJ|accessdate=28 July 2012|year=2009|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-569584-7|page=222}}</ref> She had a younger brother named Kunal and one half-sister Poonam, who was the child of Bharti's father's first marriage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bollyspice.com/7597/remembering-divya-bharti|title=Remembering Divya Bharti|publisher=BollySpice|accessdate=17 August 2013|date=September 2006}}</ref> Actress [[Kainaat Arora]] is her second cousin.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://movies.ndtv.com/bollywood/divya-bhartis-cousin-kainaat-arora-to-make-bollywood-debut-with-grand-masti-634510|title=Divya Bharti's cousin Kainaat Arora to make Bollywood debut with Grand Masti|publisher=Movies.ndtv.com|date=9 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nShe spoke [[Hindi]], [[English language|English]] and [[Marathi language|Marathi]] fluently. In her early years, Bharti was known for her bubbly personality<ref name=\"fpj\">{{cite news|url=http://www.freepressjournal.in/weekend/four-bollywood-beauties-unsolved-death-mysteries/784073|title=Four Bollywood beauties unsolved death mysteries - Free Press Journal|work=www.freepressjournal.in|accessdate=14 June 2016}}</ref> and for her doll-like looks.<ref name=\"toi\">{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/Bollywood-mysteries-that-remain-unsolved-even-today/Bollywood-mysteries-that-remain-unsolved-even-today/photostory/38140566.cms|title=Bollywood mysteries that remain unsolved even today - The Times of India|date=30 September 2014|work=The Times of India|accessdate=14 June 2016}}</ref> Bharti studied at Maneckji Cooper High School in [[Juhu|Juhu, Mumbai]]. She was an average student and completed 9th standard before pursuing an acting career.<ref>{{cite news|quote= Divya, who can be arguably termed India's Greta Garbo...|url=http://divyabharti.tumblr.com/biography|title= Early Life of Divya Bharti|work=Divya Bharti Portal|accessdate=28 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nIn 1988, Bharti was discovered by filmmaker Nandu Tolani. Upon seeing her, Tolani insisted on signing her for one of his films. At that time, Bharti was in the ninth standard (in ninth grade). She was originally scheduled to make her screen debut in ''[[Gunahon Ka Devta (1990 film)|Gunahon Ka Devta]]'' in 1988, but her role was cancelled.<ref name=\"Yashpal(journalist.)2006\">{{cite book|author1=Yashpal|author2=Anand (journalist)|title=Divya|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iyCOxf1_UWAC|accessdate=28 July 2012|date=1 January 2006|publisher=Sahitya Akademi|isbn=978-81-260-1797-3|page=266}}</ref> Kirti Kumar noticed Bharti at a video library, and thus was eager to sign her for his project ''[[Radha Ka Sangam]]'' opposite [[Govinda (actor)|Govinda]], as he was searching for a new face. Weeks later, Kumar met with Dilip Shankar and managed to release Bharti from her contract. After taking dancing and acting lessons for months to prepare for her role, Bharti was eventually dropped and replaced by [[Juhi Chawla]].<ref name=\"Yashpal(journalist.)2006\"/> Though the reasons remain unclear, it was speculated that Kumar's possessiveness over Bharti and her childish nature were the cause of her replacement.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.merepix.com/2013/12/remembering-actress-divya-bharti-rare-photos-videos.html|title=Remembering Actress Divya Bharti \u2013 Rare Photos & Videos|work=merepix.com|accessdate=27 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nBharti's career was stalled until [[D. Ramanaidu]], [[Cinema of Andhra Pradesh|Telugu]] film producer, offered her ''[[Bobbili Raja]]'' opposite his son [[Daggubati Venkatesh]]. Without hoping for success after experiencing many failures in [[Bollywood]], she commenced shooting in [[Andhra Pradesh]] for her screen debut. The film was released in the summer of 1990 and became a colossal hit.<ref name=\"Bharti1981\">{{cite book|author=Ma Satya Bharti|title=Death Comes Dancing: Celebrating Life With Bhagwan Shree Rajneesh|url=https://archive.org/details/deathcomesdancin00saty|url-access=registration|accessdate=28 July 2012|year=1981|publisher=Routledge & Kegan Paul|isbn=978-0-7100-0705-6|page=[https://archive.org/details/deathcomesdancin00saty/page/183 183]}}</ref> ''Bobbili Raja'' remains to this day one of the most popular [[Cinema of Andhra Pradesh|Telugu]] movies. That same year, Bharti acted in only one [[Tamil language|Tamil]] film, ''[[Nila Penne]]'' opposite [[Anand (actor)|Anand]]. The film was critically and financially unsuccessful.<ref name=\"Bharti1981\"/>\n\nIn box office ratings, she figured next to [[Vijayshanti]]. In 1991, Bharti had back-to-back hits, including ''[[Rowdy Alludu]]'' and ''[[Assembly Rowdy]]'', opposite actors [[Chiranjeevi]] and [[Mohan Babu]].<ref>{{cite book|title=India today|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=clRDAAAAYAAJ|accessdate=28 July 2012|year=2002|publisher=Thomson Living Media India Ltd.|page=224}}</ref> Later that year, Bharti began filming [[A. Kodandarami Reddy]]'s action romance ''[[Dharma Kshetram]]'' under Sri Rajeev Productions. Bharti got to work with Telugu film actor [[Nandamuri Balakrishna]].<ref name=\"Outlook\">{{cite book|title=Outlook|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0-kvAQAAIAAJ|accessdate=28 July 2012|volume=43|date=19 June 2003|publisher=Hathway Investments Pvt Limited}}</ref>\n\nWhile Bharti celebrated her success in [[Andhra Pradesh]], [[Bollywood]]'s top directors were eager to sign the [[Cinema of Andhra Pradesh|Telugu]] superstar for their upcoming films. Bharti's first [[Bollywood]] film was ''[[Vishwatma]]'' opposite [[Sunny Deol]], directed by [[Rajiv Rai]], and was released on 2 January 1992. The film was Super-Hit at the box office and gained Bharti wider recognition from the public as well as film critics.<ref name=\"JhaBachchan2005\">{{cite book|author1=Subhash K. Jha|author2=Amitabh Bachchan|title=The Essential Guide to Bollywood|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=s1mVuJJPm3UC|accessdate=28 July 2012|date=1 November 2005|publisher=Roli Books Private Limited|location=Mumbai|isbn=978-81-7436-378-7|page=275}}</ref> Notably, the music of the film was successful, especially the song \"Saat Samundar\", which became a favourite, and put Bharti in the limelight of Bollywood.<ref name=\"JhaBachchan2005\"/>\n\nA week later, Bharti's next film, [[Lawrence D'Souza]]'s romantic drama ''[[Dil Ka Kya Kasoor]]'', alongside [[Prithvi (actor)|Prithvi]] released. The film was not a box office success but was recognized for its music.<ref name=\"India today\">{{cite book|title=India today|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iWpDAAAAYAAJ|accessdate=28 July 2012|year=1994|publisher=Thomson Living Media India Ltd.}}</ref> After the box office failure of the film, she was quoted as saying, \"I wanted to prove myself. But I've fallen flat on my face. Now, I have to begin my climb all over again. Yet, I'm positive that one day, success will be mine.\" (''Stardust'', March 1992).<ref name=\"Somaaya2007\">{{cite book|author=Bhawana Somaaya|title=Hema Malini: The Authorized Biography |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jhoIGQAACAAJ|accessdate=28 July 2012|year=2007|publisher=Lotus Collection|isbn=978-81-7436-467-8 |page=320}}</ref>\nIn March 1992, [[David Dhawan]]'s ''[[Shola Aur Shabnam (1992 film)|Shola Aur Shabnam]]'' was released. It was popular with critics and was a box office hit in India,<ref name=\"career\">{{cite web |url= http://daily.bhaskar.com/article/divya-bharti-created-world-record-1541276.html |title=Divya Bharti created world record |date=12 November 2010 }}</ref> marking Bharti's first major hit in Bollywood. It also gave a big boost to [[Govinda (actor)|Govinda]]'s career and launched [[David Dhawan]] as an established director.<ref name=\"David Dhawan's work' \">{{cite web |url= http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-interview-with-rohit-dhawan/20110922.htm |title= I've been critical about my father David Dhawan's work'|work=[[Rediff.com]]|accessdate=28 July 2012}}</ref>\nShortly thereafter, Bharti achieved further success in [[Raj Kanwar]]'s ''[[Filmfare]]''- award-winning love story ''[[Deewana (1992 film)|Deewana]]''<ref name=\"Shah Rukh Khan Starrer Deewana' \">{{cite web |url= http://www.rediff.com/movies/report/filmmaker-raj-kanwar-passes-away/20120203.htm |title= movie that launched actors Shah Rukh Khan|work=[[Rediff.com]]|accessdate=28 July 2012}}</ref> starred veteran actor [[Rishi Kapoor]] and newcomer [[Shah Rukh Khan|Shahrukh Khan]], which is regarded as one of the biggest blockbuster hits of 1992. Her performance in ''Deewana'' was highly appreciated.<ref name=\"Fan-tastic fantasies\">{{cite news |url=http://www.asianage.com/books/fan-tastic-fantasies-633 |title= Kriti Kapoor lives in a self-inflicted shrine made for Divya Bharti|newspaper=[[The Asian Age]]|accessdate=3 March 2010}}</ref> She received a [[Lux Face of the Year]] title. Critics reported that Bharti belonged to a new breed of [[Hindi]] film actors who broke away from character stereotypes. Bharti and [[Shah Rukh Khan|Shahrukh Khan]] won the [[Filmfare Award for Lux New Face of the Year]] and [[Filmfare Award for Best Male Debut]] respectively.<ref name=\"India today\"/> By July 1992, Bharti's work in ''[[Deewana (1992 film)|Deewana]]'' was said to have earned her more recognition.\n\nShe had several other Hindi releases that year, among them ''[[Jaan Se Pyaara]]'', which featured Bharti alongside [[Govinda (actor)|Govinda]] once again, ''[[Geet (1992 film)|Geet]]'' opposite [[Avinash Wadhawan]], ''[[Dushman Zamana]]'' alongside [[Armaan Kohli]] and ''[[Balwaan]]'' which marked the debut of [[Sunil Shetty]].<ref name=\"Dawar2006\">{{cite book|author=Ramesh Dawar|title=Bollywood Yesterday-Today-Tomorrow|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TO6Fmi8FraUC|accessdate=28 July 2012|date=1 January 2006|publisher=Star Publications|location=New Delhi|isbn=978-1-905863-01-3|page=144}}</ref> The latter being a low budget film, achieved moderate success. In October, [[Hema Malini]]'s ''[[Dil Aashna Hai]]'', which once again featured her opposite [[Shah Rukh Khan|Shahrukh Khan]] was released, which didn't do as well at the box office. Divya's performance as a bar dancer who sets out to find her birth mother was however appreciated.<ref name=\"flaunted her well toned talent\">{{cite web|url=http://www.amarujala.com/Cinema/Dream-Girl-Hema-Malini-become-Hidinba-2571-1.html |title=Malini-become-Hidinba |publisher=amarujala.Com |accessdate=19 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120303144558/http://www.amarujala.com/Cinema/Dream-Girl-Hema-Malini-become-Hidinba-2571-1.html |archivedate=3 March 2012 }}</ref> Bharti decided to act in one Telugu movie per year in order to not disappoint her Telugu audience. Thus, ''[[Chittamma Mogudu]]'' was released at the end of 1992, starring once again the popular couple of Bharti and [[Mohan Babu]].{{citation needed|date=June 2016}}The ensemble film ''[[Kshatriya (film)|Kshatriya]]'' in which she co-starred alongside [[Sunny Deol]], [[Sanjay Dutt]] and [[Raveena Tandon]] was the last film to be released during Bharti's lifetime on March 26, 1993.<ref name=\"GulzarNihalani2003\">{{cite book|author1=Gulzar|author2=Govind Nihalani|author3=Saibal Chatterjee|title=Encyclopaedia of Hindi Cinema|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8y8vN9A14nkC|accessdate=28 July 2012|year=2003|publisher=Popular Prakashan|isbn=978-81-7991-066-5|page=659}}</ref>\n\nBharti's sudden death on April 5, 1993 left several films incomplete. She was more than halfway through the filming of ''[[Laadla (1994 film)|Laadla]]'' at the time of her death and the film was reshot with [[Sridevi]] replacing her. She was replaced in several other films she had not completed such as ''[[Mohra]]'', ''[[Kartavya (1995 film)|Kartavya]]'', ''[[Vijaypath]]'', [[Dilwale (1994 film)|''Dilwale'']], and ''[[Andolan (1995 film)|Andolan]]''.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Rachit Gupta|title=Flashback Friday: Forever young - Divya Bharti|url=http://www.filmfare.com/features/flashback-friday-forever-young-divya-bharti-3370.html|accessdate=14 June 2016|work=filmfare.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author1=Anjali Muthanna|title=What happens to incomplete films when actors die? - Times of India|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/kannada/movies/news/What-happens-to-incomplete-films-when-actors-die/articleshow/26794860.cms|accessdate=14 June 2016|work=The Times of India|date=4 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Divya Bharti: Death remains unsolved mystery|url=http://www.jagran.com/entertainment/bollywood-divya-bharti-death-remains-unsolved-mystery-10164837.html|accessdate=14 June 2016|work=Jagran|date=25 February 2013}}</ref> Some films which Bharti had not started shooting for were subsequently shelved, such as ''Parinaam'' with [[Akshay Kumar]], ''Do Kadam'' with [[Salman Khan]], ''Kanyadaan'' with Rishi Kapoor, ''Bajrang'' with [[Sunny Deol]] and ''Chal Pe Chal'' with [[Jackie Shroff]].\n\nShortly before her death, she had completed filming for ''[[Rang (1993 film)|Rang]]'' and ''[[Shatranj (1993 film)|Shatranj]]'' which were released posthumously several months later and achieved moderate success. Although she had completed filming her scenes for both films, a dubbing artist was used as she never got the chance to dub for the films. Her incomplete [[Telugu language|Telugu]] film ''[[Tholi Muddhu]]'' was partly completed by actress [[Rambha (actress)|Rambha]], who slightly resembled Bharti and hence was used as her body double to complete her remaining scenes and the film released in October 1993. She was also supposed to play the role of Bhavani in the Telugu film [[Allari Premikudu|''Allari Premikudu'']], but due to her sudden death her role was given to Rambha.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kavirayani |first1=Suresh |title=The dark side of showbiz spotlight |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/telugu/movies/news/The-dark-side-of-showbiz-spotlight/articleshow/20426428.cms|work=The Times of India|accessdate=17 June 2016|date=4 June 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nDivya Bharti met director-producer [[Sajid Nadiadwala]] through [[Govinda (actor)|Govinda]] at the shooting of ''[[Shola Aur Shabnam (1992 film)|Shola Aur Shabnam]]'', and they were married on 10 May 1992.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u0926\u093f\u0935\u094d\u092f\u093e \u092d\u093e\u0930\u0924\u0940 \u0915\u0947 \u092e\u094c\u0924 \u0915\u0940 \u0905\u0938\u0932\u0940 \u0935\u091c\u0939 |url=https://www.newstrend.news/68072/bollywood-actress-divya-bharti-death-mystery/ |website=newstrend.news |publisher=Newstrend |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref> Divya and Sajid were married in a private ceremony, with the presence of her hairdresser-friend Sandhya, Sandhya's husband and a [[Qazi]] at Nadiadwala's Tulsi Buildings residence (in Mumbai).<ref name=ht>{{cite news|author1=Roshmila Bhattacharya|title=Too young to die|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/entertainment/too-young-to-die/story-YJq1kkah1FcCqZSn7aDCsK.html|accessdate=14 June 2016|work=Hindustan Times|date=24 April 2011}}</ref> She converted to [[Islam]] after her marriage and changed her name to Sana Nadiadwala.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Khalid Mohamed|title=After 23 Years, Divya Bharti\u2019s Death Still Remains a Mystery|url=http://www.thequint.com/entertainment/2016/04/04/divya-bharti-mysterious-death-sajid-nadiadwala-shah-rukh-khan-deewana-rishi-kapoor|accessdate=14 June 2016|work=The Quint}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=PHOTOS: Who killed Divya Bharti ?|url=http://www.saharasamay.com/gallery/photo-gallery/entertainment-photogallery/photos-who-killed-divya-bharti-/676478779/5/31178.html#photo|accessdate=14 June 2016|work=Sahara Samay}}</ref> Divya Bharti's Marriage with Sajid Nadiadwala was kept secret, so that it would not affect her prosperous film career, which was on peak at that time.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bollywood mysteries that remain unsolved even today |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/photo-features/bollywood-mysteries-that-remain-unsolved-even-today/bollywood-mysteries-that-remain-unsolved-even-today/photostory/38140566.cms |website=Times of India |publisher=Times of India |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=\u0907\u0928 6 \u090f\u0915\u094d\u091f\u094d\u0930\u0947\u0938\u0947\u0938 \u0928\u0947 \u091b\u093f\u092a\u093e\u0915\u0930 \u0930\u0916\u0940 \u0925\u0940 \u0905\u092a\u0928\u0940 \u0936\u093e\u0926\u0940 \u0915\u0940 \u0916\u092c\u0930 |url=https://www.newstrend.news/281778/bollywoods-secret-marriages/ |website=newstrend.news |publisher=Newstrend |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Death ==\nIn the late evening hours of April 5, 1993, Bharti fell off the balcony window of her fifth-floor apartment in Tulsi Buildings, [[Versova, Mumbai|Versova]], [[Andheri West]] (Mumbai). When her guests [[Neeta Lulla]], Neeta's husband Shyam, Divya's maid Amrita, and neighbors realised what had happened, she was rushed in an ambulance to the emergency department at [[Cooper Hospital]] lying in a pool of blood, where she died. The immediate cause of death was stated as severe head injuries and internal bleeding. She was cremated on 7 April 1993 at the Vile Parle crematorium, Mumbai.<ref name=\"ht\" /><ref>{{cite news|author1=Farhana|url=http://www.filmfare.com/interviews/remembering-divya-bharti-12829.html|title=Remembering Divya Bharti|date=5 April 2016|work=filmfare.com|accessdate=14 June 2016}}</ref> \n\nThe reason of her fatal fall was never established and several theories circulated in the media during that time, including falling under the influence of alcohol (she was believed to be a heavy drinker); being pushed by someone (suspects included people present at the apartment) \u2013 deliberately, accidentally or otherwise; Bharti's habit of doing thrilling activities; suicide; murder; and the involvement of her husband and [[Organised crime in India|underworld]] mafia.<ref name=\"fpj\" /><ref>{{cite news|author1=Neha Borkar|url=http://www.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bollywood/10-celebrities-who-died-under-mysterious-circumstances-230516.html|title=10 Celebrities Who Died Under Mysterious Circumstances|date=25 February 2015|work=indiatimes.com|accessdate=14 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author1=Priyanko Sarkar|url=http://www.mensxp.com/entertainment/bollywood/8845-10-bollywood-personalities-who-died-mysteriously.html|title=10 Bollywood Personalities Who Died Mysteriously|work=www.mensxp.com|accessdate=14 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.saharasamay.com/gallery/photo-gallery/photos-who-killed-divya-bharti-/676478779/31176.html|title=PHOTOS: Who killed Divya Bharti ?|work=Sahara Samay|accessdate=14 June 2016}}</ref> The investigation was closed in 1998 by [[Mumbai police]] and the reason of death was stated as an accidental death.<ref name=\"toi\" /> \n\n== Legacy ==\nHer death caused a major loss to [[Bollywood]] film industry. The directors & producers, with whom she worked cited that \"If she was alive, she would have been to this day the most successful Indian actress just after [[Sridevi]] & [[Madhuri Dixit]]\".  Talat Jani, who worked with her in ''[[Rang (1993 film)|Rang]],'' said that \" when in the morning, I came across the news that Divya had fallen to her death, I was immensely shocked. It seemed to me as if anyone has torn the [[Novel]] of Divya from the middle.\"\n\n[[Bollywood]] legend [[Dev Anand]] made a movie titled ''[[Chargesheet (film)|Chargesheet]]'' which was loosely based on her death and the mystery surrounding it and was released on 30 September 2011.\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Year !! Title !! Role !! Language !! Notes\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |1990\n|''[[Bobbili Raja]]''\n| Rani\n| [[Telugu language|Telugu]]\n| Debut film\n|-\n|''[[Nila Pennae]]''\n| Surya\n| [[Tamil language|Tamil]]\n| Debut Tamil film\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |1991\n|''[[Rowdy Alludu]]''\n|Rekha\n|rowspan=\"3\" |Telugu\n|\n|-\n|''Naa Ille Naa Swargam''\n|Lalitha\n|\n|-\n|''[[Assembly Rowdy]]''\n| Pooja\n| \n|-\n| rowspan=\"12\" |1992\n|''[[Vishwatma]]''\n| Kusum\n| rowspan=\"10\" |Hindi\n| Debut Hindi film\n|-\n|''[[Dil Ka Kya Kasoor]]''\n| Seema/Shalani Saxena\n|\n|-\n|''Andhaa Insaaf''\n|Payel\n|\n|-\n|''[[Shola Aur Shabnam (1992 film)|Shola Aur Shabnam]]''\n| Divya Thapar\n|\n|-\n|''[[Deewana (1992 film)|Deewana]]''\n| Kaajal\n|[[Filmfare Award for Lux New Face of the Year]]\n|-\n|''[[Jaan Se Pyaara]]''\n| Sharmila\n|\n|-\n|''[[Balwaan]]''\n| Deepa\n|\n|-\n|''[[Dushman Zamana]]''\n| Seema\n|\n|-\n|''[[Dil Aashna Hai]]''\n| Laila / Sitara\n|\n|-\n|''[[Geet (1992 film)|Geet]]''\n| Neha\n| \n|-\n|''[[Chittemma Mogudu]]''\n| Chittemma\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Telugu\n|\n|-\n|''[[Dharma Kshetram]]''\n| Mythili\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\" |1993\n|''[[Dil Hi To Hai (1993 film)|Dil Hi To Hai]]''\n| Bharati\n| Hindi\n|\n|-\n|''[[Kshatriya (film)|Kshatriya]]''\n| Tanvi Singh\n| Hindi\n| Last release during her lifetime\n|-\n|''[[Tholi Muddhu]]''\n| Divya\n| Telugu\n| Posthumous release; partly completed by South Indian actress [[Rambha (actress)|Rambha]]\n|-\n|''[[Rang (1993 film)|Rang]]''\n| Kajal\n| Hindi\n| Posthumous release\n|-\n|''[[Shatranj (film)|Shatranj]]''\n| Renu\n| Hindi\n| Last release after her death\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name| id=0080251 | name = Divya Bharti }}\n* [http://www.divyabhartiportal.com/ Official website of Divya Bharti]\n{{FilmfareAwardBestFemaleDebut}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bharti, Divya}}\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:1993 deaths]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Accidental deaths from falls]]\n[[Category:Accidental deaths in India]]\n[[Category:Indian film actresses]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses in Telugu cinema]]\n[[Category:Actresses in Hindi cinema]]\n[[Category:Actresses in Tamil cinema]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indian actress}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=August 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Divya Bharti\n| image              = Divya Bharti.jpg\n| image_size         = \n| caption            = Bharti in 1993\n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|df=yes|1974|02|25}}\n| birth_place        = [[Mumbai]]\n| death_date         = {{Death date |df=yes|1993|04|05|1974|2|25}} (age 19)\n| death_place        = [[Versova, Mumbai]]\n| death_cause        = Accidental fall\n| nationality        = Indian\n| occupation         = Actress\n| image_caption      = Divya Bharti in 1992\n| height             = 5 feet 6 inches (168 cm)\n| yearsactive        = 1990\u20131993\n| spouse             = [[Sajid Nadiadwala]]<br><small>(1992 \u20131993; her death)</small>\n}}\n\n'''Divya Bharti''' (25 February 1974 \u2013 5 April 1993) was an Indian film actress, who starred in a number of commercially successful [[Hindi cinema|Hindi]] and [[Telugu cinema|Telugu]] motion pictures in the early 1990s.<!--Known for her acting versatility, vivacity and beauty, she is regarded as one of the most popular & highest paid actresses of her time.-->\n\nBharti aspired to a career in films at a young age and started to get offers at age 14, while she was doing some modeling assignments. After several unsuccessful attempts, she made her debut with a lead role in the successful [[Cinema of Andhra Pradesh|Telugu]] drama ''[[Bobbili Raja]]'' (1990) at age 16. After featuring in a number of high-grossing Telugu films, she progressed to [[Bollywood|Hindi cinema]] in 1992 with the action thriller ''[[Vishwatma]]''. Bharti went on to have commercial success, appearing in films such as ''[[Shola Aur Shabnam (1992 film)|Shola Aur Shabnam]]'' and ''[[Deewana (1992 film)|Deewana]]'', the latter of which led to her winning the [[Filmfare Award for Best Female Debut]].<ref name=\"actress\">{{cite news|title=Shah Rukh Khan's autobiography Twenty Years In A Decade to release soon|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report_shah-rukh-khan-s-autobiography-twenty-years-in-a-decade-to-release-soon_1552261|accessdate=28 July 2012|newspaper=[[Daily News and Analysis]]|date=7 June 2011}}</ref> She acted in over a dozen consistently-successful Hindi films over a year span, which is to date an unbroken record in [[Hindi cinema]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://daily.bhaskar.com/article/divya-bharti-created-world-record-1541276.html|title=Divya Bharti created world record|work=daily.bhaskar.com|accessdate=27 September 2015|date=12 November 2010}}</ref> \n\nBharti died on 5 April 1993, aged 19,<ref name=Rediff>{{cite web|title=Looking at stars who died young|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-death-anniversary-of-divya-bharti-and-kurt-cobain/20110405.htm|publisher=[[Rediff.com]]|accessdate=27 December 2011|date=26 December 2011}}</ref> from head injuries sustained after falling off the balcony of her fifth-floor apartment at [[Versova, Mumbai]]. She was at a high-time in her career at the time of her death, and due to this had received significant speculation from the Indian film industry and audiences.<ref name=\"life on screen\">{{cite news|author=Chopra, Sonia|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-04-07/news-interviews/31300649_1_biopic-bollywood-debut-mystery|newspaper=[[The Times of India]]|title=Divya's journey: The 'ageless' diva over the years|date=7 April 2008|accessdate=19 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The sad truth: Celebs who committed suicide|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/gallery/actresses-who-committed-suicide-jiah-khan-kuldeep-randhawa-divya-bharti-in-their-prime/10/11881.html|website=[[India Today]]|accessdate=19 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and family==\nDivya Bharti was born in [[Bombay]] (present-day [[Mumbai]]) to Om Prakash Bharti, an insurance officer, and his wife, Meeta Bharti.<ref name=\"SaariCa\u1e6d\u1e6dop\u0101dhy\u0101\u1e8fa2009\">{{cite book|author1=Anil Saari|author2=P\u0101rtha Ca\u1e6d\u1e6dop\u0101dhy\u0101\u1e8fa|title=Hindi Cinema: An Insider's View|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dqzQOgAACAAJ|accessdate=28 July 2012|year=2009|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-569584-7|page=222}}</ref> She had a younger brother named Kunal and one half-sister Poonam, who was the child of Bharti's father's first marriage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bollyspice.com/7597/remembering-divya-bharti|title=Remembering Divya Bharti|publisher=BollySpice|accessdate=17 August 2013|date=September 2006}}</ref> Actress [[Kainaat Arora]] is her second cousin.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://movies.ndtv.com/bollywood/divya-bhartis-cousin-kainaat-arora-to-make-bollywood-debut-with-grand-masti-634510|title=Divya Bharti's cousin Kainaat Arora to make Bollywood debut with Grand Masti|publisher=Movies.ndtv.com|date=9 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nShe spoke [[Hindi]], [[English language|English]] and [[Marathi language|Marathi]] fluently. In her early years, Bharti was known for her bubbly personality<ref name=\"fpj\">{{cite news|url=http://www.freepressjournal.in/weekend/four-bollywood-beauties-unsolved-death-mysteries/784073|title=Four Bollywood beauties unsolved death mysteries - Free Press Journal|work=www.freepressjournal.in|accessdate=14 June 2016}}</ref> and for her doll-like looks.<ref name=\"toi\">{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/Bollywood-mysteries-that-remain-unsolved-even-today/Bollywood-mysteries-that-remain-unsolved-even-today/photostory/38140566.cms|title=Bollywood mysteries that remain unsolved even today - The Times of India|date=30 September 2014|work=The Times of India|accessdate=14 June 2016}}</ref> Bharti studied at Maneckji Cooper High School in [[Juhu|Juhu, Mumbai]]. She was an average student and completed 9th standard before pursuing an acting career.<ref>{{cite news|quote= Divya, who can be arguably termed India's Greta Garbo...|url=http://divyabharti.tumblr.com/biography|title= Early Life of Divya Bharti|work=Divya Bharti Portal|accessdate=28 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nIn 1988, Bharti was discovered by filmmaker Nandu Tolani. Upon seeing her, Tolani insisted on signing her for one of his films. At that time, Bharti was in the ninth standard (in ninth grade). She was originally scheduled to make her screen debut in ''[[Gunahon Ka Devta (1990 film)|Gunahon Ka Devta]]'' in 1988, but her role was cancelled.<ref name=\"Yashpal(journalist.)2006\">{{cite book|author1=Yashpal|author2=Anand (journalist)|title=Divya|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iyCOxf1_UWAC|accessdate=28 July 2012|date=1 January 2006|publisher=Sahitya Akademi|isbn=978-81-260-1797-3|page=266}}</ref> Kirti Kumar noticed Bharti at a video library, and thus was eager to sign her for his project ''[[Radha Ka Sangam]]'' opposite [[Govinda (actor)|Govinda]], as he was searching for a new face. Weeks later, Kumar met with Dilip Shankar and managed to release Bharti from her contract. After taking dancing and acting lessons for months to prepare for her role, Bharti was eventually dropped and replaced by [[Juhi Chawla]].<ref name=\"Yashpal(journalist.)2006\"/> Though the reasons remain unclear, it was speculated that Kumar's possessiveness over Bharti and her childish nature were the cause of her replacement.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.merepix.com/2013/12/remembering-actress-divya-bharti-rare-photos-videos.html|title=Remembering Actress Divya Bharti \u2013 Rare Photos & Videos|work=merepix.com|accessdate=27 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nBharti's career was stalled until [[D. Ramanaidu]], [[Cinema of Andhra Pradesh|Telugu]] film producer, offered her ''[[Bobbili Raja]]'' opposite his son [[Daggubati Venkatesh]]. Without hoping for success after experiencing many failures in [[Bollywood]], she commenced shooting in [[Andhra Pradesh]] for her screen debut. The film was released in the summer of 1990 and became a colossal hit.<ref name=\"Bharti1981\">{{cite book|author=Ma Satya Bharti|title=Death Comes Dancing: Celebrating Life With Bhagwan Shree Rajneesh|url=https://archive.org/details/deathcomesdancin00saty|url-access=registration|accessdate=28 July 2012|year=1981|publisher=Routledge & Kegan Paul|isbn=978-0-7100-0705-6|page=[https://archive.org/details/deathcomesdancin00saty/page/183 183]}}</ref> ''Bobbili Raja'' remains to this day one of the most popular [[Cinema of Andhra Pradesh|Telugu]] movies. That same year, Bharti acted in only one [[Tamil language|Tamil]] film, ''[[Nila Penne]]'' opposite [[Anand (actor)|Anand]]. The film was critically and financially unsuccessful.<ref name=\"Bharti1981\"/>\n\nIn box office ratings, she figured next to [[Vijayshanti]]. In 1991, Bharti had back-to-back hits, including ''[[Rowdy Alludu]]'' and ''[[Assembly Rowdy]]'', opposite actors [[Chiranjeevi]] and [[Mohan Babu]].<ref>{{cite book|title=India today|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=clRDAAAAYAAJ|accessdate=28 July 2012|year=2002|publisher=Thomson Living Media India Ltd.|page=224}}</ref> Later that year, Bharti began filming [[A. Kodandarami Reddy]]'s action romance ''[[Dharma Kshetram]]'' under Sri Rajeev Productions. Bharti got to work with Telugu film actor [[Nandamuri Balakrishna]].<ref name=\"Outlook\">{{cite book|title=Outlook|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0-kvAQAAIAAJ|accessdate=28 July 2012|volume=43|date=19 June 2003|publisher=Hathway Investments Pvt Limited}}</ref>\n\nWhile Bharti celebrated her success in [[Andhra Pradesh]], [[Bollywood]]'s top directors were eager to sign the [[Cinema of Andhra Pradesh|Telugu]] superstar for their upcoming films. Bharti's first [[Bollywood]] film was ''[[Vishwatma]]'' opposite [[Sunny Deol]], directed by [[Rajiv Rai]], and was released on 2 January 1992. The film was Super-Hit at the box office and gained Bharti wider recognition from the public as well as film critics.<ref name=\"JhaBachchan2005\">{{cite book|author1=Subhash K. Jha|author2=Amitabh Bachchan|title=The Essential Guide to Bollywood|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=s1mVuJJPm3UC|accessdate=28 July 2012|date=1 November 2005|publisher=Roli Books Private Limited|location=Mumbai|isbn=978-81-7436-378-7|page=275}}</ref> Notably, the music of the film was successful, especially the song \"Saat Samundar\", which became a favourite, and put Bharti in the limelight of Bollywood.<ref name=\"JhaBachchan2005\"/>\n\nA week later, Bharti's next film, [[Lawrence D'Souza]]'s romantic drama ''[[Dil Ka Kya Kasoor]]'', alongside [[Prithvi (actor)|Prithvi]] released. The film was not a box office success but was recognized for its music.<ref name=\"India today\">{{cite book|title=India today|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iWpDAAAAYAAJ|accessdate=28 July 2012|year=1994|publisher=Thomson Living Media India Ltd.}}</ref> After the box office failure of the film, she was quoted as saying, \"I wanted to prove myself. But I've fallen flat on my face. Now, I have to begin my climb all over again. Yet, I'm positive that one day, success will be mine.\" (''Stardust'', March 1992).<ref name=\"Somaaya2007\">{{cite book|author=Bhawana Somaaya|title=Hema Malini: The Authorized Biography |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jhoIGQAACAAJ|accessdate=28 July 2012|year=2007|publisher=Lotus Collection|isbn=978-81-7436-467-8 |page=320}}</ref>\nIn March 1992, [[David Dhawan]]'s ''[[Shola Aur Shabnam (1992 film)|Shola Aur Shabnam]]'' was released. It was popular with critics and was a box office hit in India,<ref name=\"career\">{{cite web |url= http://daily.bhaskar.com/article/divya-bharti-created-world-record-1541276.html |title=Divya Bharti created world record |date=12 November 2010 }}</ref> marking Bharti's first major hit in Bollywood. It also gave a big boost to [[Govinda (actor)|Govinda]]'s career and launched [[David Dhawan]] as an established director.<ref name=\"David Dhawan's work' \">{{cite web |url= http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-interview-with-rohit-dhawan/20110922.htm |title= I've been critical about my father David Dhawan's work'|work=[[Rediff.com]]|accessdate=28 July 2012}}</ref>\nShortly thereafter, Bharti achieved further success in [[Raj Kanwar]]'s ''[[Filmfare]]''- award-winning love story ''[[Deewana (1992 film)|Deewana]]''<ref name=\"Shah Rukh Khan Starrer Deewana' \">{{cite web |url= http://www.rediff.com/movies/report/filmmaker-raj-kanwar-passes-away/20120203.htm |title= movie that launched actors Shah Rukh Khan|work=[[Rediff.com]]|accessdate=28 July 2012}}</ref> starred veteran actor [[Rishi Kapoor]] and newcomer [[Shah Rukh Khan|Shahrukh Khan]], which is regarded as one of the biggest blockbuster hits of 1992. Her performance in ''Deewana'' was highly appreciated.<ref name=\"Fan-tastic fantasies\">{{cite news |url=http://www.asianage.com/books/fan-tastic-fantasies-633 |title= Kriti Kapoor lives in a self-inflicted shrine made for Divya Bharti|newspaper=[[The Asian Age]]|accessdate=3 March 2010}}</ref> She received a [[Lux Face of the Year]] title. Critics reported that Bharti belonged to a new breed of [[Hindi]] film actors who broke away from character stereotypes. Bharti and [[Shah Rukh Khan|Shahrukh Khan]] won the [[Filmfare Award for Lux New Face of the Year]] and [[Filmfare Award for Best Male Debut]] respectively.<ref name=\"India today\"/> By July 1992, Bharti's work in ''[[Deewana (1992 film)|Deewana]]'' was said to have earned her more recognition.\n\nShe had several other Hindi releases that year, among them ''[[Jaan Se Pyaara]]'', which featured Bharti alongside [[Govinda (actor)|Govinda]] once again, ''[[Geet (1992 film)|Geet]]'' opposite [[Avinash Wadhawan]], ''[[Dushman Zamana]]'' alongside [[Armaan Kohli]] and ''[[Balwaan]]'' which marked the debut of [[Sunil Shetty]].<ref name=\"Dawar2006\">{{cite book|author=Ramesh Dawar|title=Bollywood Yesterday-Today-Tomorrow|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TO6Fmi8FraUC|accessdate=28 July 2012|date=1 January 2006|publisher=Star Publications|location=New Delhi|isbn=978-1-905863-01-3|page=144}}</ref> The latter being a low budget film, achieved moderate success. In October, [[Hema Malini]]'s ''[[Dil Aashna Hai]]'', which once again featured her opposite [[Shah Rukh Khan|Shahrukh Khan]] was released, which didn't do as well at the box office. Divya's performance as a bar dancer who sets out to find her birth mother was however appreciated.<ref name=\"flaunted her well toned talent\">{{cite web|url=http://www.amarujala.com/Cinema/Dream-Girl-Hema-Malini-become-Hidinba-2571-1.html |title=Malini-become-Hidinba |publisher=amarujala.Com |accessdate=19 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120303144558/http://www.amarujala.com/Cinema/Dream-Girl-Hema-Malini-become-Hidinba-2571-1.html |archivedate=3 March 2012 }}</ref> Bharti decided to act in one Telugu movie per year in order to not disappoint her Telugu audience. Thus, ''[[Chittamma Mogudu]]'' was released at the end of 1992, starring once again the popular couple of Bharti and [[Mohan Babu]].{{citation needed|date=June 2016}}The ensemble film ''[[Kshatriya (film)|Kshatriya]]'' in which she co-starred alongside [[Sunny Deol]], [[Sanjay Dutt]] and [[Raveena Tandon]] was the last film to be released during Bharti's lifetime on March 26, 1993.<ref name=\"GulzarNihalani2003\">{{cite book|author1=Gulzar|author2=Govind Nihalani|author3=Saibal Chatterjee|title=Encyclopaedia of Hindi Cinema|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8y8vN9A14nkC|accessdate=28 July 2012|year=2003|publisher=Popular Prakashan|isbn=978-81-7991-066-5|page=659}}</ref>\n\nBharti's sudden death on April 5, 1993 left several films incomplete. She was more than halfway through the filming of ''[[Laadla (1994 film)|Laadla]]'' at the time of her death and the film was reshot with [[Sridevi]] replacing her. She was replaced in several other films she had not completed such as ''[[Mohra]]'', ''[[Kartavya (1995 film)|Kartavya]]'', ''[[Vijaypath]]'', [[Dilwale (1994 film)|''Dilwale'']], and ''[[Andolan (1995 film)|Andolan]]''.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Rachit Gupta|title=Flashback Friday: Forever young - Divya Bharti|url=http://www.filmfare.com/features/flashback-friday-forever-young-divya-bharti-3370.html|accessdate=14 June 2016|work=filmfare.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author1=Anjali Muthanna|title=What happens to incomplete films when actors die? - Times of India|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/kannada/movies/news/What-happens-to-incomplete-films-when-actors-die/articleshow/26794860.cms|accessdate=14 June 2016|work=The Times of India|date=4 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Divya Bharti: Death remains unsolved mystery|url=http://www.jagran.com/entertainment/bollywood-divya-bharti-death-remains-unsolved-mystery-10164837.html|accessdate=14 June 2016|work=Jagran|date=25 February 2013}}</ref> Some films which Bharti had not started shooting for were subsequently shelved, such as ''Parinaam'' with [[Akshay Kumar]], ''Do Kadam'' with [[Salman Khan]], ''Kanyadaan'' with Rishi Kapoor, ''Bajrang'' with [[Sunny Deol]] and ''Chal Pe Chal'' with [[Jackie Shroff]].\n\nShortly before her death, she had completed filming for ''[[Rang (1993 film)|Rang]]'' and ''[[Shatranj (1993 film)|Shatranj]]'' which were released posthumously several months later and achieved moderate success. Although she had completed filming her scenes for both films, a dubbing artist was used as she never got the chance to dub for the films. Her incomplete [[Telugu language|Telugu]] film ''[[Tholi Muddhu]]'' was partly completed by actress [[Rambha (actress)|Rambha]], who slightly resembled Bharti and hence was used as her body double to complete her remaining scenes and the film released in October 1993. She was also supposed to play the role of Bhavani in the Telugu film [[Allari Premikudu|''Allari Premikudu'']], but due to her sudden death her role was given to Rambha.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kavirayani |first1=Suresh |title=The dark side of showbiz spotlight |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/telugu/movies/news/The-dark-side-of-showbiz-spotlight/articleshow/20426428.cms|work=The Times of India|accessdate=17 June 2016|date=4 June 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nDivya Bharti met director-producer [[Sajid Nadiadwala]] through [[Govinda (actor)|Govinda]] at the shooting of ''[[Shola Aur Shabnam (1992 film)|Shola Aur Shabnam]]'', and they were married on 10 May 1992.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u0926\u093f\u0935\u094d\u092f\u093e \u092d\u093e\u0930\u0924\u0940 \u0915\u0947 \u092e\u094c\u0924 \u0915\u0940 \u0905\u0938\u0932\u0940 \u0935\u091c\u0939 |url=https://www.newstrend.news/68072/bollywood-actress-divya-bharti-death-mystery/ |website=newstrend.news |publisher=Newstrend |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref> Divya and Sajid were married in a private ceremony, with the presence of her hairdresser-friend Sandhya, Sandhya's husband and a [[Qazi]] at Nadiadwala's Tulsi Buildings residence (in Mumbai).<ref name=ht>{{cite news|author1=Roshmila Bhattacharya|title=Too young to die|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/entertainment/too-young-to-die/story-YJq1kkah1FcCqZSn7aDCsK.html|accessdate=14 June 2016|work=Hindustan Times|date=24 April 2011}}</ref> She converted to [[Islam]] after her marriage and changed her name to Sana Nadiadwala.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Khalid Mohamed|title=After 23 Years, Divya Bharti\u2019s Death Still Remains a Mystery|url=http://www.thequint.com/entertainment/2016/04/04/divya-bharti-mysterious-death-sajid-nadiadwala-shah-rukh-khan-deewana-rishi-kapoor|accessdate=14 June 2016|work=The Quint}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=PHOTOS: Who killed Divya Bharti ?|url=http://www.saharasamay.com/gallery/photo-gallery/entertainment-photogallery/photos-who-killed-divya-bharti-/676478779/5/31178.html#photo|accessdate=14 June 2016|work=Sahara Samay}}</ref> Divya Bharti's Marriage with Sajid Nadiadwala was kept secret, so that it would not affect her prosperous film career, which was on peak at that time.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bollywood mysteries that remain unsolved even today |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/photo-features/bollywood-mysteries-that-remain-unsolved-even-today/bollywood-mysteries-that-remain-unsolved-even-today/photostory/38140566.cms |website=Times of India |publisher=Times of India |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=\u0907\u0928 6 \u090f\u0915\u094d\u091f\u094d\u0930\u0947\u0938\u0947\u0938 \u0928\u0947 \u091b\u093f\u092a\u093e\u0915\u0930 \u0930\u0916\u0940 \u0925\u0940 \u0905\u092a\u0928\u0940 \u0936\u093e\u0926\u0940 \u0915\u0940 \u0916\u092c\u0930 |url=https://www.newstrend.news/281778/bollywoods-secret-marriages/ |website=newstrend.news |publisher=Newstrend |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Death ==\nIn the late evening hours of April 5, 1993, Bharti fell off the balcony window of her fifth-floor apartment in Tulsi Buildings, [[Versova, Mumbai|Versova]], [[Andheri West]] (Mumbai). When her guests [[Neeta Lulla]], Neeta's husband Shyam, Divya's maid Amrita, and neighbors realised what had happened, she was rushed in an ambulance to the emergency department at [[Cooper Hospital]] lying in a pool of blood, where she died. The immediate cause of death was stated as severe head injuries and internal bleeding. She was cremated on 7 April 1993 at the Vile Parle crematorium, Mumbai.<ref name=\"ht\" /><ref>{{cite news|author1=Farhana|url=http://www.filmfare.com/interviews/remembering-divya-bharti-12829.html|title=Remembering Divya Bharti|date=5 April 2016|work=filmfare.com|accessdate=14 June 2016}}</ref> \n\nThe reason of her fatal fall was never established and several theories circulated in the media during that time, including falling under the influence of alcohol (she was believed to be a heavy drinker); being pushed by someone (suspects included people present at the apartment) \u2013 deliberately, accidentally or otherwise; Bharti's habit of doing thrilling activities; suicide; murder; and the involvement of her husband and [[Organised crime in India|underworld]] mafia.<ref name=\"fpj\" /><ref>{{cite news|author1=Neha Borkar|url=http://www.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bollywood/10-celebrities-who-died-under-mysterious-circumstances-230516.html|title=10 Celebrities Who Died Under Mysterious Circumstances|date=25 February 2015|work=indiatimes.com|accessdate=14 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author1=Priyanko Sarkar|url=http://www.mensxp.com/entertainment/bollywood/8845-10-bollywood-personalities-who-died-mysteriously.html|title=10 Bollywood Personalities Who Died Mysteriously|work=www.mensxp.com|accessdate=14 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.saharasamay.com/gallery/photo-gallery/photos-who-killed-divya-bharti-/676478779/31176.html|title=PHOTOS: Who killed Divya Bharti ?|work=Sahara Samay|accessdate=14 June 2016}}</ref> The investigation was closed in 1998 by [[Mumbai police]] and the reason of death was stated as an accidental death.<ref name=\"toi\" /> \n\n== Legacy ==\nHer death caused a major loss to [[Bollywood]] film industry. The directors & producers, with whom she worked cited that \"If she was alive, she would have been to this day the most successful Indian actress just after [[Sridevi]] & [[Madhuri Dixit]]\".  Talat Jani, who worked with her in ''[[Rang (1993 film)|Rang]],'' said that \" when in the morning, I came across the news that Divya had fallen to her death, I was immensely shocked. It seemed to me as if anyone has torn the [[Novel]] of Divya from the middle.\"\n\n[[Bollywood]] legend [[Dev Anand]] made a movie titled ''[[Chargesheet (film)|Chargesheet]]'' which was loosely based on her death and the mystery surrounding it and was released on 30 September 2011.\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"